defines the old political order. They address the unraveling and/or reinvention of a grand compromise in global governance from a variety of theoretical perspectives and issue areas, including trade, finance, networked governance, North-South relations, and the environment. Focusing on the foundations of political authority at the global level, the contributors imagine the implications of success or failure for international economic order and political stability. Ruggie, whose work inspired many of this book's scholars, contributes a chapter on the prospects for a new global—as opposed to international—grand bargain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aGlobalizationxEconomic aspects. 0aInternational relations. 0aLegitimacy of governments. 4aBusiness and Economics : Economic History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Economic Policy.2bisacsh1 aBernstein, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Steven, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHelleiner, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIvanova, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMendelsohn, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPauly, Louis W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPauly, Louis W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPorter, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenau, James N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuggie, John Gerard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThérien, Jean-Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolfe, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https:/